1.3 Split, Train and Test:

split_obj <- initial_split(product_data_proc, prop = 0.75)
train_tbl <- training(split_obj)
test_tbl <- testing(split_obj)

1.4 Creating ML preprocessing recipe:

recipe_obj <- recipe(prod_backorder ~ ., data = train_tbl) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  prep()

split_obj<- initial_split(product_data_proc, prop = 0.75)
train_tbl<- training(split_obj)
test_tbl<- testing(split_obj)

1.9 Original plot_features()

explainer <- train_tbl %>%
  select(-prod_backorder) %>%
  lime(
    model = automl_model,
    bin_continuous = TRUE,
    n_bins = 4,
    quantile_bins = TRUE
  )
#> Warning: in_transit_qty does not contain enough variance to use quantile
#> binning. Using standard binning instead.
#> Warning: pieces_past_due does not contain enough variance to use quantile
#> binning. Using standard binning instead.
#> Warning: local_bo_qty does not contain enough variance to use quantile binning.
#> Using standard binning instead.
explanation <- test_tbl %>%
  slice(1) %>%
  select(-prod_backorder) %>%
  lime::explain(
    explainer = explainer,
    n_labels = 1,
    n_features = 8,
    n_permutations = 5000,
    kernel_width = 1
  )
#> Warning in explain.data.frame(., explainer = explainer, n_labels = 1,
#> n_features = 8, : "labels" and "n_labels" arguments are ignored when explaining
#> regression models
#>

  |                                                                      |   0%
  |                                                                            
  |======================================================================| 100%

  |                                                                      |   0%

1.10 Plotting the original explanation

plot <- plot_features(explanation = explanation, ncol = 1, cases = 1)
plot

  1. Get your custom plot_features() function to scale to multiple cases
  2. Use theme arguments to modify the look of the plot

2.1 Plot multiple cases

explanation_multi <- test_tbl %>%
  slice(1:20) %>%
  select(-prod_backorder) %>%
  lime::explain(
    explainer = explainer,
    n_labels = 1,
    n_features = 8,
    n_permutations = 5000,
    kernel_width = 1
  )
#> Warning in explain.data.frame(., explainer = explainer, n_labels = 1,
